body:
Add the ability to define virtual attributes for HTML elements in `React.DOM`. This would allow semantic attributes to be declared that would be applied to modify some other attributes on the element. They could be declared in such a way:

``` javascript
/**
 * The callback would be given access to the attribute's value,
 * and allow it to modify the other attributes of the element.
 */
function hiddenAttribute (value, attributes) {
  if (value) {
    attributes.style || (attributes.style = {});
    attributes.style.display = 'none';
  }
}

React.declareAttribute('hidden', hiddenAttribute);
```

Using it in JSX:

``` javascript
/**
 * @jsx React.DOM
 * @jsxns {"Core":"Core","Common":"Common"}
 */

var MyComponent = React.createClass({
  render: function () {
    return <div hidden={true}>...</div>;
  }
});
```

Outputs:

``` html
<div style="display: none;">...</div>
```

This would only be for `React.DOM` elements, not custom components. However, if one were to use `transferPropsTo` on a `React.DOM` element, then it would inherit the hidden attribute.

While writing this up, I haven't been able to think of any other useful attributes, so perhaps it's not as useful if there's only the single use case.

If there's buy-in for a concept like this, I'd be happy to attempt an implementation of it. Just thought I'd propose to see if it would be beneficial to anyone else for a different kind of attribute.
